The challenge of balancing quantization efficiency across different hardware platforms resonates with our work at RailMind.eu on metabolic stress self-organization architectures for edge AI.

While INT4 optimization focuses on squeezing maximum performance from existing quantization schemes, we've been exploring a different approach: architectures that self-organize under metabolic stress constraints, achieving 103μs inference latency on Raspberry Pi 5 with a 40.4KB model footprint.

The Android performance gap you're observing might benefit from considering not just better INT4 kernels, but alternative sparse activation patterns that emerge naturally under edge deployment constraints. Have you experimented with activation sparsity patterns that vary by platform capability?

