I just gave it a try, indeed now I can verify the fix without the hacking, although I found the inline completion extension is insufficient for showing the count-down(kindly correct if any misunderstanding).

Looking at canUseChat() in the main branch:
Line 376: Checks chatEntitlementService.sentiment.installed
Line 380-382: Checks ChatEntitlement which is about chat/sign-in status
Line 384: Checks quotas.chat and quotas.completions
They are all about Chat being installed, not inline completions

Luckily, as the autocompletion is now observable due to the extension, I am able to validate the fix even though the countdown is not showing:
Recalling my implementation, fractional minute is actually supported, so I tried 0.1 minute, i.e., 6 seconds, see recording below, where it shows after around 6 seconds the inline suggestion restores:

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/683862d0-c033-4bf0-b3aa-f1c6484f8982

On the other hand, during the validation showing in the recording, I found another possible bug, that is, after the snooze timeout, the inline suggestion won't be back online unless any related operation(e.g. creating new file) is conducted.
The reason is the snooze timer didn't notify the completion system to refresh when it expired, so completions only reappeared after user actions like typing or switching files.
In order to make the recording demonstrating the fix, I conveniently fixed this issue too. Shall I simply include it together with this PR or file a separate issue for that?
